    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3910976897" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3910976897" />
    <a title="GJ Refill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/61290454-gj-refill"><img alt="GJ Refill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526172186p2/61290454.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3910976897?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="GJ Refill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="GJ Refill" href="/user/show/61290454-gj-refill">GJ Refill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781418519360" href="/book/show/7627705-when-god-whispers-your-name">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3910976897" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2709655291066577048">If Max Lucado had been around when the <i>Book of Proverbs</i> was being written, maybe he could have contributed some. That was my thought near the end of <i>When God Whispers Your Name </i>, a collection of short readings with hopeful messages. Either that or maybe a Christian version of <i>Aesop’s Fables</i>.<br/><br/>Containing 28 stories, Lucado continues to impress me with his ability to take seemingly random topics and make them relevant. From a description of anger at a noisy cricket to fictionalized accounts of Old T</span>
  <span id="freeText2709655291066577048" style="display:none">If Max Lucado had been around when the <i>Book of Proverbs</i> was being written, maybe he could have contributed some. That was my thought near the end of <i>When God Whispers Your Name </i>, a collection of short readings with hopeful messages. Either that or maybe a Christian version of <i>Aesop’s Fables</i>.<br /><br />Containing 28 stories, Lucado continues to impress me with his ability to take seemingly random topics and make them relevant. From a description of anger at a noisy cricket to fictionalized accounts of Old Testament newspapers this is a charming group of stories. Much like the previous Lucado work I read (<i>God Came Near</i>), these can be read as devotionals, although they are also more entertaining than that with Lucado’s ability to create a moral to the story that almost feels like a bit of a twist. They may be quick reads, but that does not make them any less insightful.<br /><br />As with any collection, there are likely to be some weak entries, and that certainly happens here. No matter how positive something is, that doesn’t always make it the best read. Due to being slow or a little too sappy, not everything works all that well. It is to Lucado’s credit, though, that he does keep the sap to a minimum, and most writers would not be as successful as he is in avoiding being oversentimental.<br /><br />Above all else, the absolute best part of what I have read from Lucado is the overall message: God knows we are not perfect, knows that we mess up, knows that we beat ourselves up over it, and, ultimately, He still wants fellowship with us. Where we may want to give up, God does not. Very effectively, Lucado lays that out, and I cannot help but feel positive inspiration. Nothing wrong with feeling good after reading a book.<br /><br /><br />3 ½ stars out of 5</span>
  <a data-text-id="2709655291066577048" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


